{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476403"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:46:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:46:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13739"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13739"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.53,0.25,0.02,0.02,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6358"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111147"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6358"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13739"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93271"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"563"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11810"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38187"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41717"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45123"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111147"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-month-old boy presents to his General Practice clinic with his parents for a routine well-child check. He was born at 35 weeks gestation and spent two weeks in the neonatal intensive care unit for respiratory distress. He has no other significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. His mother reports that he has been growing and feeding well, although he seems to prefer softer foods.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 110/min, respiratory rate 30/min, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. His weight is at the 15th percentile. He makes eye contact and has a social smile but doesn\u0027t yet wave \u0022bye bye\u0022. He is able to roll from front to back and reach for objects. He does not sit unsupported. He vocalises with monosyllabic sounds like \u0022ba\u0022 and \u0022ga\u0022 but is not yet babbling with repetitive consonant-vowel combinations.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following developmental domains is there concern for at this visit?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Normal development","Gross motor","Fine motor","Social","Language"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDevelopmental assessment in infants requires careful consideration of the expected milestones for age, as well as the impact of any perinatal factors such as prematurity. In children born preterm, it is important to use the corrected age (chronological age minus the number of weeks born before 40 weeks gestation) when evaluating developmental progress, particularly in the first two years of life. This approach helps avoid overdiagnosis of developmental delay and ensures that expectations are appropriate for the child\u0027s neurological maturity\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case the child is making \u003Cstrong\u003Eage-appropriate progress in his developmental domains. \u003C/strong\u003EHe is rolling from front to back and reaching for objects, which are expected \u003Cstrong\u003Egross and fine motor\u003C/strong\u003E milestones for his age, especially when considering his prematurity. He demonstrates good eye contact and a social smile, indicating appropriate \u003Cstrong\u003Esocial\u003C/strong\u003E development. He is also vocalising with monosyllabic sounds, but is not yet babbling with repetitive consonant-vowel combinations. This typically emerges between 6 and 8 months with absence of two part babble considered a red flag for \u003Cstrong\u003Everbal\u003C/strong\u003E development at 9 months. Close monitoring of his language development is warranted, but at this stage no intervention is warranted, especially given his premature birth.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Babbling with repetitive consonant-vowel combinations typically emerges between 6 and 8 months of age.","Developmental surveillance should focus on domains where milestones are not yet achieved within the expected timeframe.","Prematurity may affect the timing of developmental milestones, and corrected age should be considered in assessment."],"references":["Aites J, Schonwald A. 2024. Developmental-behavioral surveillance and screening in primary care. In: UpToDate [online]. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/developmental-behavioral-surveillance-and-screening-in-primary-care","Dosman CF, Andrews D, Goulden KJ. Evidence-based milestone ages as a framework for developmental surveillance. Paediatr Child Health. 2012;17(10):561-8. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3549694/","Red Flags Early Identification Guide. In QLD Health [online]. 2024 [Cited 2025 Aug 7]. Available at: https://www.childrens.health.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0026/167093/red-flags.pdf","Behavior and Devlopment (0-5 years): Adapted from the Denver Developmental Screening Test (Denver II). In: DCHealthCheck [online]. [cited 2025 Aug 7]. Available at: https://www.dchealthcheck.net/trainings/documentation/epsdt/development.pdf","Child development: Babies (0-12 months) | The Sydney Children\u2019s Hospitals Network [Internet]. [cited 2025 Aug 9]. Available from: https://www.schn.health.nsw.gov.au/kids-health-hub/child-development/child-development-babies-0-12-months"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93271"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13739"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93271"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-09T18:21:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-09T18:21:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6358"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111147"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"t